  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "The training slows or even halts when gradients become excessively small because parameter updates during backpropagation, which is based on the size of gradients, become correspondingly smaller in layers closer to the input.",
    "Microsoft research found that making a neural network layer fit a residual mapping of the input to the output instead of fitting a new learned function helped to address the degradation problem (He et al. 2016).",
    "Formally, if H(x) is an underlying mapping that enables a layer to contribute to generalized learning, then the residual (difference) will be F(x) = H(x) -x. Algebraically, the underlying mapping becomes H(x) = F(x) + x.",
    "The interpretation here is that a residual is simply adding the layer input x back to its output, which is a learned residual function F(x) that contributes to the underlying mapping.",
    "Hence, when the output is close to the input, the residual (difference) will be small."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Microsoft research found that making a neural network layer fit a residual mapping of the input to the output instead of fitting a new learned function helped to address the degradation problem (He et al. 2016)."
  ]
}